              heading: 'The 30-Second Answer',
              body: `For most Phoenix homes built after 1995 with functional ductwork, a heat pump is the better choice right now. The federal 25C tax credit (up to $2,000), APS and SRP utility rebates ($500–$2,000 combined), and lower operating costs on the APS TOU-E rate plan make the economics compelling in a way they weren't five years ago. If your home has undersized ducts, a very large square footage (5,000+ SF), or relies heavily on natural gas for other appliances, a hybrid dual-fuel setup may still make sense — heat pump for the shoulder seasons, gas furnace backup for the coldest nights.`
            },
            {
              heading: "What a Heat Pump Actually Does in Phoenix's Climate",
              body: `A heat pump moves heat rather than generating it. In cooling mode, it works exactly like a central AC — it extracts heat from inside your home and dumps it outside. In heating mode, it reverses: it extracts heat from outdoor air (even at 30°F there's substantial heat energy available) and moves it inside. This is why heat pumps are 2–4x more efficient than electric resistance heat. In Phoenix, the heating season is mild enough (typical lows of 40–55°F in December and January) that even a basic heat pump operates at 250–350% efficiency all winter. There are zero days in a typical Phoenix winter where a modern cold-climate heat pump can't handle the load. The "heat pumps don't work in cold weather" concern is completely inapplicable to the Valley. Where Phoenix is different is the cooling season: 115°F-rated heat pumps need to be selected carefully. Not all units maintain rated capacity above 105°F ambient. We spec units tested to AHRI 210/240 at 95°F and 115°F ratings specifically, and verify the outdoor unit can handle prolonged exposure on 115°F days.`
            },
