              body: `A mid-tier variable-speed heat pump (Carrier Infinity or equivalent, 3-ton, 18 SEER2) installed in a typical Phoenix home runs $9,500–$13,500 before incentives. A comparable furnace+AC combo runs $8,000–$11,500. That seems like a heat pump premium, until you factor in: the 30% federal 25C tax credit (up to $2,000), the APS heat pump rebate ($400–$1,200 depending on SEER2 rating), the SRP heat pump rebate ($300–$600) — and those are just the day-one numbers. On operating cost, a heat pump running on APS's TOU-E rate plan replaces gas heating with electricity at roughly 3.5x efficiency. In Phoenix, where winter heating loads are modest, most homeowners see their combined heating and cooling costs drop 15–30% after switching from a furnace+AC to a heat pump. The payback period on the premium, after incentives, is typically 4–7 years.`
            },
