        relatedPosts: ['heat-pump-vs-furnace-ac-phoenix', 'aps-srp-hvac-rebate-guide', 'mini-split-vs-central-ac-phoenix'],
        content: {
          intro: `The Inflation Reduction Act's Section 25C tax credit is one of the most valuable home improvement incentives in recent memory — and one of the most confusing to actually claim. This is a step-by-step guide from someone who has walked hundreds of Phoenix Valley homeowners through the process. Note: this is educational information, not tax advice. Consult your CPA or tax professional for your specific situation.`,
          sections: [
            {
              heading: 'What the 25C Credit Actually Covers',
              body: `Section 25C of the IRS tax code, as modified by the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022, provides a tax credit of 30% of the cost of qualifying energy-efficient home improvements, including heat pumps, up to $2,000 per year for heat pumps and heat pump water heaters combined. This is a non-refundable tax credit — it reduces your tax liability dollar-for-dollar, but doesn't generate a refund beyond your tax owed. The credit covers both equipment and installation labor. If your heat pump installation totals $10,000, the credit is $3,000 — but it's capped at $2,000 for heat pumps. Qualifying equipment must meet CEE (Consortium for Energy Efficiency) Tier 2 or higher efficiency standards. For central air-source heat pumps, that currently means SEER2 ≥ 15.2, EER2 ≥ 10, and HSPF2 ≥ 7.8. We install equipment that qualifies as a matter of course.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'The AHRI Certificate: Your Most Important Document',
              body: `The AHRI (Air-Conditioning, Heating, and Refrigeration Institute) certificate is the official documentation that your specific equipment combination — outdoor unit, indoor unit (or air handler), and coil — has been tested and meets the rated efficiency specifications. You need this for the tax credit. AHRI certificates are specific to matched equipment combinations, not individual units. This is why we handle equipment selection carefully: we verify the outdoor unit, air handler, and coil are an AHRI-certified matched system at the qualifying efficiency level before we order equipment. After installation, we provide you with the AHRI certificate as part of your installation package. You'll need the certificate number, the rated SEER2/HSPF2, and the equipment model numbers when filing. We also provide a written installation summary that documents the system specifications and the address of installation.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'How to Actually File the Credit',
              body: `The 25C credit is claimed on IRS Form 5695 (Residential Energy Credits) and then carried to Schedule 3 of your Form 1040. Line 22a on Form 5695 (current version) is for qualified heat pump equipment. You'll enter the total cost (equipment + installation labor) and the form calculates your credit. Attach Form 5695 to your federal return. You do not submit the AHRI certificate to the IRS with your return — you keep it with your records in case of an audit. The IRS has recently increased scrutiny of energy credit claims, so keep your installation invoice, AHRI certificate, and contractor information together in one folder. Arizona does not currently have a state-level heat pump tax credit, but the federal credit stacks with APS and SRP utility rebates, which are separate programs you apply for directly with the utility.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'Stacking with APS and SRP Rebates',
              body: `The 25C credit and utility rebates can be used together, which is where the real savings add up. APS (Arizona Public Service) currently offers a rebate of $400–$1,200 for qualifying heat pump installations, depending on SEER2 rating and equipment type. SRP (Salt River Project) offers $300–$600. These rebates are applied after installation — you submit a rebate application with documentation (installation invoice, AHRI certificate, and contractor license information) within 90 days of installation. The rebate is paid as a credit on your utility bill or a check. We provide all the documentation you need to apply. A typical Phoenix homeowner installing a qualifying 18 SEER2 heat pump system at $11,000 installed might receive: $2,000 federal 25C credit + $1,000 APS rebate + $500 SRP rebate = $3,500 in total incentives, reducing net cost to $7,500. We track current rebate levels for both utilities and build this into every heat pump quote.`
            }
          ],
          pullQuote: '"A typical Phoenix homeowner can receive $2,000 federal credit + $1,000 APS + $500 SRP = $3,500 in incentives on a qualifying heat pump installation. Most don\'t claim all three."',
          conclusion: `The 25C credit is available through 2032, but rebate programs from APS and SRP can change annually. If you're considering a heat pump installation in the Phoenix Valley, now is a particularly good time — the stacked incentives are as strong as they've been. Skyhooked on Comfort handles all the documentation: AHRI certificate, installation summary, and rebate application assistance. Visit our <a href="/residential/heat-pump-installation" class="text-sky hover:underline">heat pump installation page</a> or call (480) 123-4567 to get a free in-home quote that includes the full incentive picture for your specific home and utility.`
        }
