    {
      params: { slug: 'oversized-ac-problems' },
      props: {
        category: 'Troubleshooting',
        categorySlug: 'troubleshooting',
        title: 'Why an Oversized AC Is Worse Than No AC at All',
        author: 'Marcus Torres',
        authorTitle: 'Master Technician',
        authorCredentials: 'EPA 608 Universal, NATE Certified',
        authorYears: '14 years with Skyhooked on Comfort',
        authorBio: "Marcus Torres has been servicing and installing HVAC systems in the Phoenix Valley since 2012. He holds EPA 608 Universal and NATE certifications and leads Skyhooked's installation team. He has diagnosed more oversized-AC problems in Phoenix homes than he can count.",
        date: 'April 18, 2026',
        readTime: '6 min read',
        relatedPosts: ['manual-j-load-calculation', 'ac-tune-up-checklist', 'heat-pump-vs-furnace-ac-phoenix'],
        content: {
          intro: `This is the conversation I have at least twice a week in Phoenix. A homeowner got a new AC installed 3 years ago. It was "the biggest unit" the contractor had. Now their house feels cold but clammy in July. Some rooms never cool down while others are freezing. The system runs for 10 minutes, shuts off, runs for 10 minutes. Energy bills are high. What went wrong? The system is oversized, and it's ruining their comfort, their air quality, and their equipment.`,
          sections: [
            {
              heading: 'What Short-Cycling Is and Why It Destroys Comfort',
              body: `An air conditioning system works best when it runs in long, steady cycles — 20–40 minutes at a stretch under typical conditions. During that run time, it cools the air AND removes humidity. Dehumidification is a critical part of AC comfort, especially in Phoenix during monsoon season (July–September) when relative humidity can spike from 10% to 50% or higher in a matter of hours. Dehumidification requires the evaporator coil to get cold enough that water vapor condenses on it. That takes time — about 15 minutes of run time for the coil to reach peak dehumidification performance. An oversized system hits your temperature setpoint in 8–10 minutes and shuts off. The coil never reaches maximum dehumidification efficiency. The result: the thermostat says 74°F, but the air feels muggy and uncomfortable at 74°F because the humidity is 55–60% instead of the ideal 40–50%.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'The Equipment Damage Oversizing Causes',
              body: `Every compressor start is a high-stress event. Oil hasn't fully circulated, pressures are unequal, and the motor draws 4–6x its running amperage during the first few seconds. A properly-sized system in Phoenix might start 4–6 times per hour on a very hot day. An oversized system might start 12–15 times per hour because each run cycle is so short. Compressors are typically rated for a certain number of starts per day; dramatically exceeding that rating accelerates wear and ultimately causes early compressor failure. We see this in Phoenix regularly: a homeowner bought a brand-new 5-ton system when their home needed 3.5 tons. Five years later, the compressor has failed — not from heat damage or lack of maintenance, but from accelerated wear due to constant short-cycling. The replacement cost is $1,800–$3,500, and the new compressor will fail early too if the root cause (oversizing) isn't corrected.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'The Phoenix Monsoon Problem',
              body: `Standard humid climates in the southeast US experience 70–80% relative humidity for months at a time. AC systems there are designed with latent (humidity removal) capacity as a key parameter. Phoenix is classified as a dry desert climate — but monsoon season from July through September regularly brings afternoon and evening humidity spikes that stress AC systems in ways their sizing didn't account for. A properly-sized AC in Phoenix should handle both the sensible load (actual air temperature cooling) and the latent load (humidity removal) during monsoon conditions. An oversized system slams the sensible load down fast and shuts off before addressing the latent load. The result is that during the Valley's entire monsoon season — which often coincides with the hottest stretch of the year — you have a house that's technically at your setpoint temperature but feels hot and uncomfortable because the humidity is uncontrolled.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'How to Know If Your System Is Oversized',
              body: `Warning signs: Short run times — if your system runs fewer than 15 minutes before shutting off on a typical summer afternoon, it may be oversized. Uneven temperatures room-to-room. High humidity inside despite the AC running. Higher-than-expected electricity bills. The system feels like it's "blasting" when it comes on rather than providing steady airflow. The definitive test is a Manual J load calculation for your home. If the calculated load is significantly smaller than your installed equipment capacity, you have an oversized system. The fix depends on the severity: for mild oversizing, adding a two-speed or variable-speed system on replacement can mitigate the problem. For severe oversizing, the duct system may also need evaluation — oversized equipment often gets paired with undersized ductwork, which creates additional problems.`
            }
          ],
          pullQuote: '"An oversized AC short-cycles and never removes humidity properly. In Phoenix monsoon season, you get cold, clammy air — the worst of both worlds. Bigger is not better."',
          conclusion: `If your new AC doesn't feel right, don't assume it's a defective unit — ask about the sizing. A diagnostic call from Skyhooked on Comfort includes an evaluation of both the equipment and the duct system. If your home was oversized, we'll tell you honestly and explain your options. Visit our <a href="/residential/ac-repair" class="text-sky hover:underline">AC repair page</a> or our <a href="/service-areas/phoenix" class="text-sky hover:underline">Phoenix service area page</a> for more. Call (480) 123-4567 — we're available 24/7.`
        }
