        title: 'AC Tune-Up Checklist: What a Real $79 Tune-Up Should Include',
        author: 'Diego Ramirez',
        authorTitle: 'NATE Certified Service Technician',
        authorCredentials: 'EPA 608 Universal, NATE Certified, ACCA Certified',
        authorYears: '11 years with Skyhooked on Comfort',
        authorBio: "Diego Ramirez joined Skyhooked on Comfort in 2015. He specializes in residential diagnostics and preventive maintenance and has performed thousands of tune-ups across the Phoenix Valley.",
        date: 'April 10, 2026',
        readTime: '5 min read',
        relatedPosts: ['oversized-ac-problems', 'ac-freezing-up-causes', 'day-in-life-hvac-technician'],
        content: {
          intro: `Every spring, Phoenix homeowners see ads for $49 and $59 AC tune-ups. Some of those are legitimate loss-leader offers from good companies. Others are "trip fee disguised as a tune-up" operations — a tech shows up, checks the thermostat, looks at the unit for 10 minutes, and recommends $400 in additional services. Here's the 22-point checklist that a real AC tune-up should cover before Phoenix summer hits.`,
          sections: [
            {
              heading: 'Outdoor Unit (Condenser) — 9 Checks',
              body: `1. Inspect and clean condenser coil fins (this is the most critical step for Phoenix — a dirty condenser can reduce cooling capacity by 15–20% and the Valley's dust and pollen clogs them every season). 2. Measure amperage draw on the compressor and compare to nameplate. Elevated draw is an early indicator of compressor stress. 3. Check and measure capacitor microfarads — capacitors degrade over time and are the single most common failure part in Phoenix heat. Replace if within 10% of minimum tolerance. 4. Inspect and test the contactor — pitted contacts cause voltage drop and compressor damage. 5. Check refrigerant pressures and compare to manufacturer spec for current ambient temperature. Low charge or high subcooling both indicate issues. 6. Measure supply and return air temperatures across the system (temperature split check). 7. Inspect disconnect, fuses, and electrical connections at the unit. Loose connections arc under load and cause failures. 8. Check fan motor amperage and blade condition. A failing fan motor can run 20 amperes over spec. 9. Inspect refrigerant line insulation on the suction line — degraded insulation causes heat absorption and reduced efficiency.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'Indoor Unit (Air Handler / Evaporator) — 8 Checks',
              body: `10. Inspect and clean evaporator coil — dirty coils restrict airflow and freeze up. In Phoenix, attic dust accumulates on indoor coils seasonally. 11. Flush and treat condensate drain line — Phoenix attic temperatures exceed 150°F in summer, which accelerates biological growth in drain pans. A blocked condensate drain causes water overflow and ceiling/drywall damage. 12. Check condensate pump operation (where installed). 13. Measure static pressure across the filter and evaporator — reveals duct restriction or airflow problems. 14. Inspect and replace air filter (we install the replacement filter you provide or use a standard pleated filter). 15. Check blower motor amperage and wheel condition. Dirty blower wheels are common in dusty Phoenix attics and dramatically reduce airflow. 16. Inspect electrical connections at the air handler — loose terminals arc and cause component failures. 17. Verify thermostat calibration and operation — check setpoint accuracy, delay settings, and proper stage sequencing on two-stage units.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'System Performance — 5 Checks',
              body: `18. Measure supply and return static pressure — the standard diagnostic for overall duct health and system airflow. 19. Check temperature split across the system (typically 16–22°F in Phoenix conditions). Outside that range indicates refrigerant, airflow, or coil issues. 20. Verify refrigerant charge by superheat or subcooling method (varies by system type) — not just pressure, which can be misleading. 21. Run full cooling cycle and monitor system behavior — listen for unusual sounds, check for short-cycling, verify both stages operate on two-stage systems. 22. Document all readings in a written report — every measurement, any findings, and any recommended work with the flat-rate price for each item. This report is yours and protects you if a different company tries to upsell the same issues next year.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'When to Schedule in Phoenix',
              body: `The ideal window for a Phoenix spring AC tune-up is March through April. By late April, temperatures start hitting the 90s regularly and our schedule fills up fast. If you call in June with a tune-up request, you'll wait — and you may be waiting during the first 110°F week. Members of our Comfort Plan get priority spring scheduling and their tune-up automatically booked. For homeowners not on a plan, we recommend booking in February or early March. A spring tune-up on a Phoenix system that was running all last summer will almost always find at least one issue — a degraded capacitor, low refrigerant from a slow leak, a dirty condenser coil — that's much cheaper to address proactively than reactively in July.`
            }
          ],
          pullQuote: '"A dirty Phoenix condenser coil reduces cooling capacity by 15–20%. In 115°F heat, that\'s the difference between comfortable and borderline dangerous. Cleaning it is step one."',
          conclusion: `A real tune-up takes 60–90 minutes and produces a written report with all measurement readings. If a "tune-up" takes 20 minutes and produces no documentation, it wasn't a tune-up — it was a marketing visit. Skyhooked on Comfort's $79 tune-up covers all 22 items above, produces a written report, and the dispatch fee is credited toward any recommended work you approve same-day. <a href="/service-areas/phoenix" class="text-sky hover:underline">Phoenix</a> and the entire Valley, scheduled online or by calling (480) 123-4567.`
        }
