        authorCredentials: 'EPA 608 Universal, NATE Certified',
        authorYears: '9 years with Skyhooked on Comfort',
        authorBio: "Jasmine Lee joined Skyhooked on Comfort in 2017. She is EPA 608 and NATE certified and specializes in helping homeowners understand efficiency ratings, equipment selection, and incentive programs.",
        date: 'April 3, 2026',
        readTime: '6 min read',
        relatedPosts: ['heat-pump-vs-furnace-ac-phoenix', 'manual-j-load-calculation', 'federal-heat-pump-tax-credit'],
        content: {
          intro: `If you bought an AC before January 1, 2023, you saw SEER ratings. If you're shopping today, you see SEER2 ratings. The numbers look lower for the same equipment, and homeowners naturally wonder if new ACs got less efficient. They didn't. Here's what actually changed and what it means when you're shopping for a new system in Phoenix.`,
          sections: [
            {
              heading: 'What SEER Was and Why It Changed',
              body: `SEER stands for Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio — it measures how many BTUs of cooling a system produces per watt-hour of electricity consumed over a cooling season. Higher SEER = more efficient. The original SEER test standard (ARI 210/240) was established in the 1980s and used test conditions that didn't fully reflect how systems operate in real homes with real ductwork. The external static pressure used in testing (the resistance the blower motor works against) was 0.1 inches of water column — far lower than what most real duct systems impose. Systems rated under this easy test condition would then perform significantly worse in actual homes with higher static pressure. Effective January 1, 2023, the Department of Energy mandated the new SEER2 standard under AHRI 210/240 2023, which uses 0.5 inches of external static pressure — much closer to real-world conditions. The test is harder, so the SEER2 numbers are lower for the same physical equipment. A 16 SEER unit under the old standard is typically equivalent to a 14.3–14.7 SEER2 unit under the new standard.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'The Minimum Efficiency Standard Change',
              body: `Along with the new test standard, DOE also raised the minimum efficiency requirements for new residential AC equipment in the Southwest (which includes Arizona). As of January 2023, new central air conditioners must meet a minimum of 14 SEER2 (previously 14 SEER under the old standard, which is equivalent to roughly 13 SEER2). In practice, this means the cheapest entry-level systems sold today are more efficient than the cheapest systems sold before 2023. The practical impact for Phoenix homeowners: you cannot buy a new 13 SEER2 central AC (it doesn't exist in the new market). The floor is 14 SEER2. Most mainstream contractor-grade equipment starts at 15 SEER2 and runs up to 22–26 SEER2 for premium variable-speed units.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'How to Compare Old and New Ratings When Shopping',
              body: `If you're comparing a quote from today to a quote you got three years ago, or comparing a new unit to your old unit's nameplate, use this rough conversion: SEER2 ≈ SEER × 0.92. So a 16 SEER system is roughly equivalent to a 14.7 SEER2 system. A 20 SEER system is roughly equivalent to an 18.4 SEER2 system. When comparing quotes from different contractors today, make sure both are quoting SEER2 ratings — any quote using SEER (not SEER2) is either quoting old inventory or using the old standard deliberately to make the number look bigger. When evaluating efficiency levels for the federal 25C tax credit, the qualifying threshold is SEER2 ≥ 15.2 for central air-source heat pumps. For central ACs (not heat pumps), the 25C credit does not apply to AC-only equipment — only heat pumps qualify for the heat pump portion of the credit.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'What Efficiency Level to Buy in Phoenix',
              body: `The right SEER2 level depends on how much you run your system, your electricity rate, and your budget. Phoenix runs cooling systems 8–10 months per year and 10–16 hours per day during summer. This is the highest utilization rate in the US for residential HVAC. The payback period for upgrading from 14 SEER2 to 18 SEER2 in Phoenix is significantly shorter than it would be in, say, Seattle. Our rough math: on APS's tiered rate plan, upgrading from 14 SEER2 to 18 SEER2 on a 3.5-ton system saves approximately $240–$360 per year in electricity. The upfront premium for 18 SEER2 over 14 SEER2 is typically $800–$1,400. That's a 3–5 year payback in Phoenix conditions — excellent by any ROI measure. The jump from 18 SEER2 to 22 SEER2 has a longer payback (6–8 years) and is harder to justify purely on economics unless you're planning to stay in the home 10+ years.`
            }
          ],
          pullQuote: '"SEER2 numbers look lower because the test is harder — not because the equipment is less efficient. A 16 SEER2 system beats a 16 SEER system in real-world performance."',
          conclusion: `The SEER2 transition improved the accuracy of efficiency ratings and raised the floor for new equipment — both good things for consumers. When you're shopping, focus on SEER2 ratings, verify they're under the current standard (not old SEER numbers), and run the payback math for Phoenix's usage pattern. We include a full efficiency comparison in every installation quote. Visit our <a href="/residential/ac-installation" class="text-sky hover:underline">AC installation page</a> or our <a href="/service-areas/scottsdale" class="text-sky hover:underline">Scottsdale service area page</a> for more. Call (480) 123-4567 to schedule a free consultation.`
        }
