    {
      params: { slug: 'ac-freezing-up-causes' },
      props: {
        category: 'Troubleshooting',
        categorySlug: 'troubleshooting',
        title: 'Why Your AC Freezes Up — and the 4 Causes',
        author: 'Marcus Torres',
        authorTitle: 'Master Technician',
        authorCredentials: 'EPA 608 Universal, NATE Certified',
        authorYears: '14 years with Skyhooked on Comfort',
        authorBio: "Marcus Torres is a Master Technician with 14 years of Phoenix Valley HVAC experience. He holds EPA 608 Universal and NATE certifications and leads Skyhooked's residential service team.",
        date: 'March 27, 2026',
        readTime: '5 min read',
        relatedPosts: ['oversized-ac-problems', 'ac-tune-up-checklist', 'manual-j-load-calculation'],
        content: {
          intro: `Ice forming on your air conditioner in the middle of a Phoenix July sounds impossible — and yet it's one of our most common emergency calls. Here's what's actually happening when your AC freezes up, the four most common causes, and what to do while you wait for a technician.`,
          sections: [
            {
              heading: 'What Happens When an AC Freezes Up',
              body: `Your AC's evaporator coil (the indoor coil) operates by circulating refrigerant that is much colder than the air passing over it. Under normal conditions, the coil surface temperature is 35–45°F — cold enough to cool the air but above freezing, so moisture condenses as liquid water and drains away. When the coil gets too cold (below 32°F), that condensing moisture freezes instead of draining. Ice accumulates on the coil, then spreads to the refrigerant lines, then can work its way down to the outdoor unit. Once a coil is significantly iced over, airflow through the system is blocked — the system can no longer cool effectively even though it's running. If you see ice on your indoor unit or on the copper refrigerant lines between indoor and outdoor units, turn the system off immediately (or switch to fan-only mode to melt the ice without running the compressor) and call for service. Running a frozen AC can damage the compressor.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'Cause 1: Restricted Airflow',
              body: `The most common cause of freezing, by a wide margin. If the evaporator coil can't get enough warm air flowing across it, the coil gets too cold and freezes. The most frequent airflow restrictors: a clogged or dirty air filter (check this first — if your filter is gray and dense, replace it immediately), a dirty evaporator coil (annual cleaning prevents this), closed or blocked supply and return registers (never close more than 20% of your registers), a failing blower motor (if the blower isn't spinning at the right speed, airflow drops). In Phoenix's dusty environment — especially in homes near undeveloped land or during monsoon season — air filters clog faster than the manufacturers' schedules suggest. We recommend Phoenix homeowners check 1-inch filters every 3–4 weeks in summer rather than monthly.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'Cause 2: Low Refrigerant Charge',
              body: `If your system has a refrigerant leak — however slow — the refrigerant charge drops over time. Low refrigerant causes the evaporator coil pressure to drop below normal operating range, which drops the coil temperature below freezing. The leak needs to be located and repaired (not just the refrigerant topped off — adding refrigerant to a leaking system is an EPA violation for sealed refrigerants and a temporary fix at best). Common leak locations in Phoenix HVAC systems: the Schrader valve cores on the service ports (very common; a $15 fix), flare fittings at the line set connections that have loosened over years of thermal expansion and contraction, pinhole leaks in the evaporator coil (more common in hard-water areas and aggressive-condensate environments). A low-refrigerant system also produces the symptom of running constantly without cooling your home to setpoint — a sign the system is struggling.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'Causes 3 and 4: Dirty Coil and Low Outdoor Temperature',
              body: `A heavily fouled evaporator coil acts like a dirty filter — it restricts air movement through the coil surface, drops coil temperature, and can cause freezing even with a clean filter installed. Annual coil cleaning prevents this and is part of our standard tune-up. The fourth cause is less common in Phoenix but relevant during mild spring and fall evenings: running AC when outdoor temperatures drop below 60°F at night. Most residential AC systems aren't designed to operate efficiently below 60°F outdoor ambient. The reduced heat load on a cool night, combined with the already-cold refrigerant, can cause coil icing. If you're running AC on a spring night when outdoor temps are in the 50s, consider switching to a window open or fan mode instead — you don't need the AC, and running it below its rated range causes problems.`
            }
          ],
          pullQuote: '"Ice on your AC means airflow is blocked, refrigerant is low, the coil is fouled, or it\'s too cold outside to be running AC. Turn it off before you run the compressor on liquid refrigerant."',
          conclusion: `If your AC freezes up: turn the system to fan-only (not off entirely) to melt the ice, then turn it fully off after 30–60 minutes of fan-only mode. Check your filter first. If the filter is clean and it freezes again after restarting, call for service — you likely have a refrigerant leak or coil problem. Skyhooked on Comfort runs same-day diagnostics across the <a href="/service-areas/mesa" class="text-sky hover:underline">Mesa</a>, <a href="/service-areas/tempe" class="text-sky hover:underline">Tempe</a>, and Phoenix areas. Call (480) 123-4567 or visit our <a href="/residential/ac-repair" class="text-sky hover:underline">AC repair page</a>.`
        }
      }
    },
