              heading: 'APS (Arizona Public Service) HVAC Rebates',
              body: `APS offers rebates for residential customers replacing or installing qualifying HVAC equipment. Current APS residential rebates include: Central air conditioners rated 16+ SEER2: $200–$400 (higher rebate for higher efficiency). Air-source heat pumps rated 16+ SEER2 and 8.5+ HSPF2: $400–$1,200 (tiered by efficiency). Mini-split heat pumps rated 18+ SEER2: $200–$500 per unit. Smart thermostats: $35–$75. To qualify, APS residential customers must use an APS-approved contractor (we are), install equipment that meets the minimum efficiency thresholds, and submit a rebate application with installation invoice and AHRI certificate within 90 days of installation. APS rebates are paid as a credit on your utility bill, typically within 4–6 weeks of application approval. Important: APS rebate amounts and eligibility change periodically. The figures above reflect current program levels as of spring 2026. Confirm current amounts at aps.com/savemoney before committing to an installation.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'SRP (Salt River Project) HVAC Rebates',
              body: `SRP customers have a separate rebate program with comparable incentives. Current SRP residential rebates: Central AC systems 15+ SEER2: $150–$300. Heat pumps 15+ SEER2 / 8.2+ HSPF2: $300–$600. Mini-split systems 18+ SEER2: $150–$300 per head unit. Smart thermostats compatible with SRP Time-of-Use plans: $25–$50. SRP rebate applications are submitted through SRP's online customer portal within 90 days of installation, with installation invoice and AHRI certificate documentation. SRP rebates are issued as a check or bill credit within 60 days. If you're an SRP customer on SRP's EZ-3 or M-Power time-of-use plan, there are additional bill savings from shifting cooling to off-peak hours — a heat pump combined with a smart thermostat and a time-of-use plan can reduce your annual cooling bill by 20–30% beyond equipment efficiency gains alone.`
