    {
      params: { slug: 'mini-split-vs-central-ac-phoenix' },
      props: {
        category: 'Heat Pumps',
        categorySlug: 'heat-pumps',
        title: 'Mini-Split vs Central AC for a Phoenix Addition or ADU',
        author: 'Diego Ramirez',
        authorTitle: 'NATE Certified Service Technician',
        authorCredentials: 'EPA 608 Universal, NATE Certified, ACCA Certified',
        authorYears: '11 years with Skyhooked on Comfort',
        authorBio: "Diego Ramirez joined Skyhooked on Comfort in 2015. He specializes in residential diagnostics and has installed and serviced ductless mini-split systems across the Phoenix Valley for over a decade.",
        date: 'March 12, 2026',
        readTime: '7 min read',
        relatedPosts: ['heat-pump-vs-furnace-ac-phoenix', 'federal-heat-pump-tax-credit', 'manual-j-load-calculation'],
        content: {
          intro: `You're adding a room, finishing a garage, or building an ADU (accessory dwelling unit) on your Phoenix Valley property. Your existing central AC system is either maxed out, too old to extend, or simply too far away to reach the new space efficiently. Should you extend the existing duct system or install a ductless mini-split? Here's the honest comparison.`,
          sections: [
            {
              heading: 'The Core Differences',
              body: `Central AC uses a network of ducts to distribute conditioned air from a single air handler throughout the home. Extending a central system to a new space means running new ductwork from the air handler — possible if the system has available capacity and the physical path for ductwork isn't too long or complex. A ductless mini-split is a separate system: an outdoor condenser unit connected via a refrigerant line set (no ductwork) to one or more indoor air handler units (heads) mounted on the wall or ceiling of the space being conditioned. Each head conditions its space directly, with no duct losses. Mini-splits are typically heat pump systems, meaning they both heat and cool. For an addition or ADU in Phoenix, the key variables are: distance from the existing air handler, available capacity in the existing system, whether the space needs dedicated temperature control, and your budget.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'When a Mini-Split Is the Right Answer for Phoenix',
              body: `Mini-splits win in several common Phoenix scenarios. First, garage conversions or ADUs. A detached or semi-detached ADU typically can't be efficiently served by the main home's central system — the duct run would be long, the load calculations don't work for a shared system, and an ADU often has separate occupancy. A mini-split serves it as an independent system with independent temperature control, energy metering, and no impact on the main home's AC capacity. Mitsubishi, Daikin, and LG units rated for Phoenix's 115°F ambient are our standard specs for Valley installations. Second, new additions with complex routing. If extending ductwork would require penetrating multiple walls, running through the attic for 40+ feet, or creating duct system imbalances in the existing home, a mini-split is often cleaner and cheaper. Third, spaces with different occupancy schedules. A home office that's occupied 8 hours a day doesn't benefit from being on the same zone as the rest of the house. A mini-split that only runs when the room is occupied saves energy year-round.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'When Extending Central AC Makes More Sense',
              body: `Central system extension wins when: The addition is physically close to the air handler (within 20–30 feet), the duct path is straightforward, and the existing system has available capacity after a load calculation. The aesthetic preference is for no visible wall units. The homeowner wants everything on one thermostat and one system. The system is new enough that the extension won't stress it. A well-designed duct extension with proper Manual D calculations can work perfectly and is often $1,500–$2,500 less expensive than a mini-split for a single room. The risk is that most contractors extend duct systems without doing load calculations, which results in the new room either getting too much or too little airflow, and the rest of the house getting worse distribution.`
            },
            {
              heading: 'Cost Comparison in Phoenix',
              body: `A typical single-zone ductless mini-split installation in Phoenix (one outdoor unit + one indoor head, 9,000–18,000 BTU for a garage or ADU, quality brand like Mitsubishi or Daikin) runs $3,500–$5,500 installed. Multi-zone systems (one outdoor unit serving 2–4 indoor heads) run $6,500–$12,000 for the full system. A duct extension for a single room addition (straightforward path, properly designed) runs $1,800–$3,500. For ADUs requiring a full independent system (not an extension), mini-splits are almost always the right call — the duct infrastructure for a separate structure would cost as much as the mini-split anyway. Heat pump mini-splits are eligible for the federal 25C tax credit if they meet CEE Tier 2 efficiency thresholds (most Mitsubishi and Daikin units qualify). This can recover 30% of the installed cost up to $2,000.`
            }
          ],
          pullQuote: '"For a Phoenix ADU or detached garage conversion, a mini-split is almost always the right answer — independent control, no duct losses, and eligible for the 30% federal tax credit."',
          conclusion: `The right answer depends on your specific addition — there's no universal winner. We offer free consultations that include a load calculation for the new space and an honest comparison of both options with installed cost estimates. Visit our <a href="/residential/heat-pump-installation" class="text-sky hover:underline">heat pump installation page</a> for more on our mini-split installations, or our <a href="/service-areas/gilbert" class="text-sky hover:underline">Gilbert service area page</a> — Gilbert's rapid new construction makes this a frequent question there. Call (480) 123-4567 to schedule a free consultation.`
